A simple version of the charges against Sam Bankman-Fried would be somethin=
g like =E2=80=9Cpeople deposited money at his crypto exchange, FTX, and he =
stole it and gave it to his crypto trading firm, Alameda Research, which  s=
quandered it on dumb crypto trades and endorsement deals.=E2=80=9D
But this story is not exactly right. There was not money sitting in custome=
r accounts that was then transferred to Alameda accounts and squandered. FT=
X was a futures exchange; it  did not keep money in a box for customers. Th=
e money in your FTX account was just money that FTX owed you. Nor did Alame=
da need to=C2=A0steal=C2=A0the money; FTX was a leveraged futures exchange,=
 and traders like Alameda could, in the ordinary course of business,=C2=A0b=
orrow=C2=A0money from FTX based on their crypto positions.=C2=A0The problem=
, ultimately, at FTX, was that it owed customers a lot of money, but it cou=
ldn=E2=80=99t pay them, because Alameda owed FTX a lot of money, but it cou=
ldn=E2=80=99t pay it, because it had squandered=C2=A0the money on dumb cryp=
to trades and endorsement deals.
This distinction seems=C2=A0nitpicky, but it is important. The story in the=
 first paragraph is obviously illegal, but the story in the second paragrap=
h might not be. A story like =E2=80=9Cwe owed a lot of customers money, but=
 our biggest customer owed us money, and the market moved against that cust=
omer and it defaulted on its obligations to us, so we couldn=E2=80=99t pay =
our other customers,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0can=C2=A0be legitimate, an embarrassing =
accident but not=C2=A0fraud. (As I  keep  saying, it  kind of happened in t=
he legitimate regulated market for nickel futures=C2=A0last year.)
Instead, to prove fraud, prosecutors need to prove some=C2=A0lies. The evid=
ence of fraud is not just =E2=80=9Cpeople put money at FTX and the money=C2=
=A0ended up with Alameda, which squandered it=E2=80=9D:=C2=A0That could hap=
pen legally. The evidence of fraud has to be something more like =E2=80=9Cp=
eople put money at FTX and it ended up with Alameda=C2=A0in ways that FTX s=
aid it wouldn=E2=80=99t.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CAlameda owed us money, and defau=
lted=E2=80=9D is not=C2=A0in itself=C2=A0evidence of fraud. But if FTX was =
going around saying things like =E2=80=9Cwe have made it impossible for Ala=
meda to owe us money and default,=E2=80=9D then that turned out to be a lie=
. And=C2=A0that is fraud.
I have  said this  before, and I think some people have found it annoying. =
People want this case to be=C2=A0simple: The money was stolen,=C2=A0all of =
this stuff about leveraged futures trading is a hand-waving distraction. Bu=
t I think it is clear, from the trial so far, that the=C2=A0prosecutors=C2=
=A0know what they have to prove. They are doing what I would: They are tryi=
ng to prove that Bankman-Fried was going around lying to people about how m=
uch customers (including Alameda) could owe to FTX, and how carefully FTX m=
anaged the risk of any customer defaulting on its obligations.
For instance, on Friday, they  played a recording of Bankman-Fried lying to=
=C2=A0me=C2=A0about it. He was on Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Odd Lots=C2=A0po=
dcast in August 2021 to talk about crypto market structure; here are the  a=
udio and the=C2=A0transcript. (This is not  the infamous=C2=A0Odd Lots=C2=
=A0episode, the one about  the box.)=C2=A0One thing we talked about was how=
 FTX handles liquidations. A lot of leveraged crypto exchanges had a proble=
m: They sat between people making bets on=C2=A0crypto, crypto was volatile,=
 and if Bitcoin went up (or down) a lot, people who were long (short) Bitco=
in made a lot of money, while people who were short (long) lost a lot of mo=
ney. For the exchange to pay the people who made money, the people who lost=
 money had to pay up, and they often did not. Bankman-Fried said:

Clawbacks is sort of like the word that people used for that. And there wer=
e exchanges where like each week they say like, congrats, you did good trad=
ing, you get paid 86.2% of your PNL this week. You know, the other 13.8 wen=
t to bail people out.
And it just happened week after week after week, there's millions of per da=
y of losses of customers to that, which is not how you want to end up.=C2=
=A0

He contrasted FTX=E2=80=99s solution to the problem, which was to have a li=
quidation engine=C2=A0that automatically closed out traders=E2=80=99 positi=
ons when they got too close to losing money. The idea was that, with consta=
nt monitoring of the position, well calibrated margin requirements, instant=
 liquidation and good risk management, you=E2=80=99d never end up in a situ=
ation where a losing trader owed the exchange money: Traders post collatera=
l for their trades, and all losing trades are closed out before the collate=
ral is exhausted. (Back when he was a financial celebrity, Bankman-Fried ar=
gued that this sort of automated continuous margining would make markets sa=
fer, and  pitched it to traditional financial regulators.) Of course this i=
s not absolutely risk-free =E2=80=94=C2=A0sometimes prices move faster than=
 you can liquidate =E2=80=94=C2=A0so it needs to be backstopped; the exchan=
ge needs some capital or insurance so that it can pay out customers even if=
 one customer loses too much money too quickly. FTX had that too, an insura=
nce fund to cover losses that its liquidation engine did not prevent.
On  Friday,=C2=A0FTX=E2=80=99s=C2=A0former chief technology officer, Gary W=
ang, who has pleaded guilty and is cooperating with prosecutors,  testified=
 about this. Prosecutors  played a clip of me asking, essentially, if FTX e=
ver needed that insurance, or if the liquidation engine was good enough to =
prevent losses. =E2=80=9CDo you guys regularly have blowouts that you're no=
t made whole,=E2=80=9D I asked.
  [2]
=C2=A0Bankman-Fried replied:
It's a good question. We don't have big issues. Like we've never had a day,=
 I think,=C2=A0where there's more money that we've lost in blowouts to reve=
nue that we made just from trading fees. And on most days it's effectively =
$0 costs. So this is not like a big deal for us. I mean, it's a big deal to=
 think about, but like economically, it hasn't been a big cost to us.
Nope! Molly White  reported from Wang=E2=80=99s testimony:

At one point in 2021 a trader was able to exploit a bug in FTX's margin sys=
tem to take on a huge position in MobileCoin, which ultimately resulted in =
hundreds of millions of dollars in losses for FTX.
This more than exhausted the insurance fund, so SBF allegedly told Wang to =
have Alameda "take on" the loss. According to Wang, SBF said this was becau=
