At Vox Media=E2=80=99s Code Conference on September 27, Yaccarino reiterate=
d the claim about returning advertisers during an interview, saying that =
=E2=80=9C90% of the top 100 advertisers have returned to the platform.=E2=
=80=9D
But in our latest analysis, Media Matters found that the company=E2=80=99s =
ad revenue is still decimated. The company has earned an average monthly ad=
 revenue of $69.5 million from roughly 1,900 average monthly advertisers in=
 the last 11 months =E2=80=94 42% less revenue and 28% fewer advertisers th=
an in the 11 months before Musk acquired the company.=C2=A0
What=E2=80=99s more, during Yaccarino=E2=80=99s tenure as CEO, the majority=
 of Twitter=E2=80=99s top 100 advertisers pre-Musk have spent just a fracti=
on =E2=80=94 at least 90% less =E2=80=94 of what they spent in the 12 weeks=
 prior to Musk=E2=80=99s acquisition.
During the September 27 interview, Yaccarino also claimed, =E2=80=9CIn the =
last 12 weeks alone, about 1,500 [advertisers] have returned. So whether it=
 is small business or big brands, right? Like AT&T, Visa, Nissan, all retur=
ning.=E2=80=9D Of those three companies she specifically mentioned, AT&T is=
 the only one that was a top advertiser pre-Musk, and the company has spent=
 just $781 in the last 12 weeks =E2=80=94 99.96% less than the more than $1=
.77 million it spent during the 12 weeks before Musk=E2=80=99s acquisition.
Visa and Nissan are similarly spending just a fraction of what they spent p=
re-Musk. Visa spent just $10, and Nissan spent just $687, in the last 12 we=
eks =E2=80=94 99.99% and 99.77% less than they respectively spent during th=
e 12 weeks before Musk=E2=80=99s acquisition.

I wonder if you can pay $10 to target Twitter ads just at Elon Musk, so he =
sees that you are still advertising and doesn=E2=80=99t  get mad at you.

