th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;"> described=C2=A0Wang=E2=80=99s testimony</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The prosecution grilled Wang on a single, damn=
ing column in FTX=E2=80=99s databases. Called =E2=80=9Callow_negative,=E2=
=80=9D it allowed Alameda to have a negative balance. Alameda could withdra=
w money even when its accounts didn=E2=80=99t have any, and it had an enorm=
ous line of credit. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Normal customers =E2=80=94 the defense objecte=
d to =E2=80=9Cnormal=E2=80=9D but was overruled =E2=80=94 could be automati=
cally liquidated, but not Alameda. Bankman-Fried =E2=80=9Ctold me a few tim=
es to make sure that Alameda=E2=80=99s account is never liquidated on FTX,=
=E2=80=9D Wang said. =E2=80=9CThe code addition was the result of those con=
versations.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The amount that Alameda was allowed to go nega=
tive began to creep up. Around 2019 or 2020, Wang checked the database and =
discovered that Alameda was negative by about $200 million, which was more =
than the $150 million FTX made in revenue. That had to mean Alameda was tak=
ing customer money.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Seems bad! Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Bob Van Vo=
ris, Ava Benny-Morrison and Yueqi Yang <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/32969259.256422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZX=
