 background-color: #ccc;"> Media Matters reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At Vox Media=E2=80=99s Code Conference on Sept=
ember 27, Yaccarino reiterated the claim about returning advertisers during=
 an interview, saying that =E2=80=9C90% of the top 100 advertisers have ret=
urned to the platform.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in our latest analysis, Media Matters foun=
d that the company=E2=80=99s ad revenue is still decimated. The company has=
 earned an average monthly ad revenue of $69.5 million from roughly 1,900 a=
verage monthly advertisers in the last 11 months =E2=80=94 42% less revenue=
 and 28% fewer advertisers than in the 11 months before Musk acquired the c=
ompany.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What=E2=80=99s more, during Yaccarino=E2=80=99=
s tenure as CEO, the majority of Twitter=E2=80=99s top 100 advertisers pre-=
Musk have spent just a fraction =E2=80=94 at least 90% less =E2=80=94 of wh=
at they spent in the 12 weeks prior to Musk=E2=80=99s acquisition.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">During the September 27 interview, Yaccarino a=
lso claimed, =E2=80=9CIn the last 12 weeks alone, about 1,500 [advertisers]=
 have returned. So whether it is small business or big brands, right? Like =
AT&amp;T, Visa, Nissan, all returning.=E2=80=9D Of those three companies sh=
e specifically mentioned, AT&amp;T is the only one that was a top advertise=
r pre-Musk, and the company has spent just $781 in the last 12 weeks =E2=80=
=94 99.96% less than the more than $1.77 million it spent during the 12 wee=
ks before Musk=E2=80=99s acquisition.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Visa and Nissan are similarly spending just a =
fraction of what they spent pre-Musk. Visa spent just $10, and Nissan spent=
 just $687, in the last 12 weeks =E2=80=94 99.99% and 99.77% less than they=
 respectively spent during the 12 weeks before Musk=E2=80=99s acquisition.<=
/p>
</blockquote>
